[normal]).
[normal] Bavaria offers an interesting variant of MMP: it uses open-list MMP, where Bavarians vote for individual party list candidates, not closed party lists. It does not allow for the dual listing of candidate names 
[normal]in the particular single-member constituency in which a candidate stands
[normal], because the constituency candidates' names would be on the ballot papers twice. These candidates, however, 
[normal]must
[normal] be dual candidates and are on their parties' ballot paper lists everywhere else in the electoral region.
[normal] It should be pointed out, for the sake of accuracy that Hungary’s system, and Italy’s between 1993-2005, are
[normal]/were
[normal] only semi-proportional.
[normal] The ban on dual candidacy in Ukraine was introduced prior to the 2002 parliamentary elections – by the same party that 
[normal]not long afterwards 
[normal]attempted to fix the result of the 
[normal]p
[normal]residential election and poison the main opposition candidate.
[normal] In debates preceding the 2006 GOWA, particular attention focused on the example of the 2003 constituency contest in Clwyd West, where three defeated constituency candidates all ended up being elected as list AMs.
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]Report of the Electoral Commission on the Review of the MMP Voting System
[normal], 2012; available at:
[normal]http://www.mmpreview.org.nz/have-your-say/final-report
[normal].
[normal] One might reasonably question the extent to which voters had been inf
[normal]ormed about, never mind endorsed, the dual candidacy ban in the 2005 general election.
[normal] 
[normal]The issue was barely discussed in the main Labour manifesto, which stated only that 
[normal]“
[normal]In 
[normal]Wales we will develop democratic devolution by creating a stronger
[normal] 
[normal]Assembly with enhanced legislative powers and a reformed structure
[normal] 
[normal]and electoral system to make the exercise of Assembly responsibilities
[normal] 
[normal]clearer and more accountable to the public
[normal]” (p.108, 
[normal]Britain Forward not Back
[normal])
[normal]. 
[normal]The dual candidacy b
[normal]an 
[normal]was 
[normal]only mentioned explicitly 
[normal]o
[normal]n pp.108-110 of 
[normal]the 
[normal]Welsh Labour ma
[normal]nifesto, 
[normal]Wales Forward not Back
[normal].
